1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,900
Think about the last time you ate a bowl of rice.

2
00:00:02,900 --> 00:00:04,720
You didn't wonder who grew it.

3
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:06,440
Almost no one does.

4
00:00:06,440 --> 00:00:09,200
Here's the number that changed how I think about that.

5
00:00:09,200 --> 00:00:12,720
In America, the average farmer is 58 years old.

6
00:00:12,720 --> 00:00:15,780
More than 40% are over 65.

7
00:00:15,780 --> 00:00:16,640
In Thailand,

8
00:00:16,640 --> 00:00:20,260
where rice paddies once passed from parent to child like a birthright,

9
00:00:20,260 --> 00:00:21,880
the story is the same.

10
00:00:21,880 --> 00:00:24,600
The land is aging, the children left.

11
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:26,880
So who grows the food next?

12
00:00:26,880 --> 00:00:28,860
The answer starts with math.

13
00:00:28,860 --> 00:00:30,840
Farming costs years,

14
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:33,200
years of weather that doesn't cooperate,

15
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:34,800
yields that don't arrive,

16
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,000
seasons you gamble on and lose.

17
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:38,240
And the income?

18
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:39,660
It arrives by harvest,

19
00:00:39,660 --> 00:00:42,440
not by paycheck, not on time.

20
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:47,720
A young person who moves from a Thai village to Bangkok can earn dramatically more in a year,

21
00:00:47,720 --> 00:00:49,440
not because cities are better,

22
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:51,840
because a paycheck is something you can point to.

23
00:00:51,840 --> 00:00:54,880
A failed harvest is something you absorb alone.

24
00:00:54,880 --> 00:00:57,340
But the math isn't the whole story.

25
00:00:57,340 --> 00:00:59,200
Even if the income was fair,

26
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:02,160
there's something else, an invisible tax.

27
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:05,080
In Thailand and across most of Southeast Asia,

28
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:06,880
the farm is where you came from,

29
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:08,660
not where you're going.

30
00:01:08,660 --> 00:01:14,260
Generations of parents who worked the soil sent their children to school with one unspoken prayer.

31
00:01:14,260 --> 00:01:16,560
Please, not this.

32
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:18,160
Degrees meant desks,

33
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:20,460
desks meant something better.

34
00:01:20,460 --> 00:01:23,020
There's no LinkedIn profile for organic farmer,

35
00:01:23,020 --> 00:01:27,220
no performance review for growing food without chemicals.

36
00:01:27,220 --> 00:01:30,040
The work that I do, the 5 AM wake-ups,

37
00:01:30,040 --> 00:01:31,920
the soil under my fingernails,

38
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:34,240
the rows I walk before breakfast,

39
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:38,540
none of it shows in the metrics the modern world uses to measure a life.

40
00:01:38,540 --> 00:01:45,020
We built a world that rewards what it can count and what you grow in the ground is very hard to count.

41
00:01:45,020 --> 00:01:47,520
I am one of the people who stayed.

42
00:01:47,520 --> 00:01:49,520
Every morning I walk our rows,

43
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:50,980
check the soil with my hands,

44
00:01:50,980 --> 00:01:54,560
smell the moisture before the rows come into focus.

45
00:01:54,560 --> 00:01:57,140
Then I come inside and open a laptop.

46
00:01:57,140 --> 00:01:59,100
I'm teaching myself to code.

47
00:01:59,100 --> 00:02:00,980
I'm building things with AI,

48
00:02:00,980 --> 00:02:02,920
not because I want to leave the farm,

49
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:07,040
but because the farm is exactly where that kind of building belongs.

50
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:08,780
The farm taught me patience.

51
00:02:08,780 --> 00:02:10,860
The code taught me precision.

52
00:02:10,860 --> 00:02:13,420
It turns out those are the same skill.

53
00:02:13,420 --> 00:02:15,900
So why don't young people want to farm?

54
00:02:15,900 --> 00:02:17,620
Maybe the real question is,

55
00:02:17,620 --> 00:02:20,120
what did we teach them to want instead?

56
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:22,560
We told them the numbers were wrong.

57
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:25,140
We told them the soil was beneath them.

58
00:02:25,140 --> 00:02:30,340
We never told them that what grows in the ground can grow into something entirely new.

59
00:02:30,340 --> 00:02:32,580
Someone grew that bowl of rice.

60
00:02:32,580 --> 00:02:36,100
Someone who stayed when every signal told them to leave.

61
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:40,060
The bravest generation of farmers isn't the one that planted the past.

62
00:02:40,060 --> 00:02:43,396
It's the one brave enough to plant something the world hasn't seen yet.
